As a travel content creator, my 2022 LG Gram has become an essential tool for working on the road, even in the most challenging conditions. To learn more about the LG gram and other products for working on the move, check out their Instagram @lg_tech.it #LGgram #laptop

No shower. Sleep deprived. Dehydrated. Dirt under the fingernails. Sticky from $1 cotton candy train tacos. No place I'd rather be🌏

It's been a few years since I’ve traveled on an extreme budget and in my last challenge, I traveled across Thailand with only $1/hour. It was a reminder that you don’t need the newest iPhone, fashionable clothes or reservations at a fancy restaurant to see the world. 

It takes a certain type of grit to travel without the comforts of home and I respect the backpackers who take that as a challenge💪

When I first started backpacking 6+ years ago, I had to learn how to be resourceful. A quote that has always stuck with me is from one of my favorite movies, Ratatouille 🐭 

"You must be imaginative, strong-hearted. You must try things that may not work, and you must not let anyone define your limits because of where you come from. Your only limit is your soul. What I say is true—anyone can cook... but only the fearless can be great."

Anyone can travel, but only the fearless can be great 👣

The full video from this adventure is now on my YouTube channel😅

From the illuminated Colosseum to the Pantheon, exploring Rome by night is my favorite way to see this ancient city. The best part is that you can see so many historic piazzas and churches within an hour or less of walking around the Pantheon neighborhood. The entire area feels like an open air museum and although there are a dense concentration of tourists here, there are certainly less crowds at night.

At dusk, the cobblestone streets are filled with a candlelit ambience and you can’t help but feel you are traveling back in time.

Standing in the same places where emperors and philosophers once stood is truly a once in a lifetime experience. 

You should add this magical experience to your bucket list! 

Photos by @maxwell_grover

Santorini, the land of endless blue skies and white-washed buildings, is the most iconic island in Greece. But is it worth all the hype?🤔

The answer is both yes and no. While the island's beauty is undeniable, the crowds can be overwhelming. To truly experience the magic of Santorini, it's all about finding the right balance. Visit during shoulder season, seek out the lesser-known spots, and immerse yourself in the local culture.

However, I traveled to Santorini in early May, which some consider to be shoulder season, and the crowds were already in full swing. This is to be expected in places as famous as Santorini but it comes at a cost to the overall experience and that may not be something you are willing to compromise. 

If you're looking for a more intimate and authentic experience, you’ll want to venture off the beaten path and explore the more hidden gems of Greek islands. This spring and summer, escape the crowds and experience the best-kept secrets of Greece - the picturesque island of Skopelos, the charming Ionian island of Paxos, and the rugged beauty of Lesvos.

From serene landscapes to charming villages, these underrated islands offer a true taste of authentic Greek life. Now I want to hear about your favorite islands in Greece and where you would recommend traveling to get away from the crowds this summer! Let me know if the comments 💬

🚨Every Solo Traveler Should Do This🚨

When traveling alone, make sure at least one person knows your location and itinerary details. 

Traveling alone is safe and highly encouraged but it's always best to be prepared by having a support system. This can be as simple as, “if you don’t hear from me for 48 hours, check in.” 

Methods of location sharing:

⭐️ Google Maps, Apple and Android have location sharing features where someone can see your phone location in real time. There are also a variety of apps that offer these services as well. 

⭐️ Forwarding hotel and itinerary information via email or text. If your plans change, make sure to let your person know.

It can also be helpful to give your support person the contact information of local police or your embassy in the rare circumstances they would ever need to contact them.

Location sharing is also a great way for worried loved ones to feel more at ease when you're traveling ✌️ 😇

As always, when traveling alone make sure to use common sense, avoid intoxication and stay in after dark 🙏  #solofemaletravel

THE BIG NEWS IS FINALLY HERE: I’m going to be attempting to travel around the world in an electric vehicle! 

I’m joining forces with Ford Motor Company to push the limits of electric vehicle travel in the new, all-electric Ford Explorer. This journey is inspired by Aloha Wanderwell, who in 1922 set out in the Ford Model T to become the first woman to drive around the world. 

Following in Aloha’s tracks 100 years later, I’ll be leading an expedition around the globe with the Ford Explorer. The new, all-electric Ford Explorer is built in Europe for Europe and it's revolutionizing electric vehicle travel. This is going to be one of the most challenging adventures I have ever embarked on and I’m beyond excited to share every step of the journey with you online.  

You can learn more about this project and the new electric Ford explorer on the Ford European YouTube Channel. #ExploringReinvented #Ford #ad #FordExplorer #ElectricCar

100 years ago, a woman named Aloha Wanderwell set off on one of the most epic and daring journeys ever undertaken - to drive a vehicle around the world. Despite incredible hardships and against all odds, this amazing pioneer of overland travel ventured 380,000 miles across 80 countries in five years and became the first woman to circumnavigate the world. And she did it all in a Ford Model T.

This year, I am going to be reinventing Aloha’s journey as I attempt to travel around the world in the new, ELECTRIC Ford Explorer. The Ford Explorer was built in Europe, for Europe which is where our journey will begin later in 2023. Ford is pushing the limits of what is possible when it comes to electric vehicle travel, and I can’t wait to see where this adventure will take us. 

If you want to learn more about this project and the new Ford Explorer, check out my full video on YouTube! #ExploringReinvented #Ford #ad #FordExplorer #ElectricCar

✅Bucket List: Snowboarding trip in the Alps 🏂❄️🏔️

Zermatt is, without a doubt, the cutest mountain town I've ever visited. The wooden chalets, charming cafes, and narrow cobblestone streets all give this place a special kind of magic. And don't even get me started on the views of the Matterhorn!😍 The snow-covered peaks and valleys are truly awe-inspiring. 

When I was taking the train to Zermatt from Zurich, the train was delayed for hours due to an avalanche because there was a huge storm that day. Thankfully they were able to clear the tracks which meant there was an unbelievable amount of fresh snow waiting on the other side!😆

The powder was deep and the trails were endless, making for an unforgettable snowboarding experience. I've also never had a better après ski view! 🍻 

After a long day on the slopes, nothing beats decompressing in the warm saunas @schlosshotelzermatt (best hotel spa I've ever experienced!)

 If you're looking for a magical winter getaway, I highly recommend visiting this Swiss gem.

This is going to change everything. To learn more about this project and the new, all-electric Ford Explorer, watch the full video on the Ford European YouTube channel. #ExploringReinvented #Ford #ad #FordExplorer #ElectricCar

Every corner of Angkor Wat is a world of wonder just waiting to be discovered🌏✨ 

The ancient temples have an unparalleled charm that transports you to a different era. As you wander through the labyrinthine ruins, you'll witness intricate carvings, towering spires, and rich history that feels like stepping into a dream where time stands still.

If you are planning a visit to Angkor Wat in Siem Reap, here are my top 3 travel tips to make the most of your experience:

👣 Beat the crowds and heat by arriving early in the morning or later in the afternoon. You'll avoid the busiest times and get to witness the stunning sunrise or sunset.

👚 Dress appropriately by wearing clothes that cover your shoulders and knees. This is a sign of respect in Cambodian culture and is required to enter the temples.

🚗 Hire a knowledgeable local driver but do not hire a guide. A good driver in Siem Reap is essential but in my opinion, having a guide when walking around the temples limits your ability to explore. 

Have you been to Cambodia? 🇰🇭 Share your travel tips in the comments below! 

Photos by @maxwell_grover

Melkam Fasika (Happy Easter!) Ethiopia 🇪🇹 

Fasika, Ethiopia's Easter celebration, is a sacred holiday in the Ethiopian Orthodox religion that commemorates the resurrection of Jesus Christ. After a 55 day fast, thousands of pilgrims gather in Lalibela’s rock hewn churches to pray, sing hymns, read scripture and light candles together. 

The beauty of the Midnight Mass ceremony is indescribable, as the church is illuminated by the soft glow of flickering candles, creating a sense of intimacy and spirituality. Being able to witness this cultural tradition was a humbling and unforgettable experience. 

The trip was made even more special by the incredible group of travelers that I shared it with, and the memories we made will last a lifetime 🕯️ ✨🫶

Photos by @storiesmatter @alivelikethewind @cory.s.martin

CLEAREST Water in the World 💧 

The water in the Silfra Fissure is incredibly pure and has over 300ft of visibility. The water here has been filtered through porous underground lava for up to 100 years which gives it unparalleled clarity. The fissure is formed from  the Eurasian and American tectonic plates drifting apart🌍

The water may be slightly above freezing, but a buoyant dry suit will keep you warm while you marvel at the canyon walls stretching deep beneath the surface. The colors of the blue water and green algae are stunning, making this a surreal and unforgettable diving experience that you must add to your bucket list!✨

For those of you visiting Iceland, you should reach out to @thedivingisland to visit the Silfra Fissure!

After traveling to over 50 countries alone, I've learned two golden rules that have helped me stay safe and make the most out of my trips.

First, I never get intoxicated. Being alert and aware of my surroundings is crucial, and alcohol can impair my judgment and make me vulnerable to dangerous situations. Plus, traveling is already tiring enough, and I want to make sure I have the energy to explore and enjoy my trip to the fullest.

Second, I always plan to be back at my accommodation before nightfall. While it's tempting to stay out and explore the nightlife, it's important to prioritize safety. By avoiding being out at night, I reduce my risk of encountering potential dangers or getting lost in unfamiliar places. Plus, I can wake up early and start my day refreshed and ready to explore!

Remember, it's essential to trust your instincts, do your research, and have a plan when traveling alone. By following these simple guidelines, you can travel safely and fearlessly!✨🌎 #solotravel #traveltips #solofemaletravel

What is happening here 😂

While visiting the countryside of Buenos Aires, I stumbled across this very interesting display of affection. This caught me off guard because I have never seen a man and an animal share such a deep connection. 

As it turns out, what I witnessed here was a training technique called Doma India which has deeply influenced many gauchos in Argentina. The purpose is to create a strong bond of trust and harmony between the gaucho and their horse. 

For centuries, the Argentine horse has been both a working tool and a loyal companion to gauchos. Doma India involves a year-long process of taming the horse according to its natural instincts, without inflicting fear or pain, while simultaneously earning its trust and loyalty. 

Have you ever seen anything like this before?

Tell me about your favorite countries🌍 

“What is your favorite country?” 

This is the question I’m asked the most often. It is such a difficult question to answer, it’s almost like being asked to choose a favorite child. I love so many different countries for different reasons since each place brings a totally unique culture and potential for once in a lifetime experiences. 

This topic is also extremely subjective. One of my favorite places in the world could be someone else’s least favorite, depending on their personal experience. 

Egypt, Indonesia, Italy, Pakistan and Venezuela happen to be a few of the many places I had incredible experiences during my travels. This comes down to the specific places I was able to see, the people I met when I was there and as always, good timing and pure luck. 

Let me know in the comments what your top 5 favorite countries are since I know it is impossible to choose just one!

And a few days after this I got✨malaria✨

Storytime:
When I was traveling across West Africa, I saw this man in a gas mask and hazmat suit fumigating outside of my hotel in Guinea. At first I didn't think anything of it which I would later come to regret...

I woke up in the middle of the night to a tight, painful feeling in my lip. In the dark, I knew I had been bitten by some kind of bug. I got out of bed to assess the swelling and when I flipped on the light switch, and was absolutely horrified at what I saw in the mirror. 

My upper lip had swollen more than three times the size! My skin was so tight it felt like it could rip open. Since it was the middle of the night and I had an early flight, I had absolutely no idea what to do. I looked like a crazy person walking through that airport the next day😂

Over the next few days, the swelling began to decrease, but I started feeling very sick. I was exhausted, had muscle aches and a fever, chills, diarrhea- the works. 

I ended up going to the hospital in Abidjan, Côte d'Ivoire. In spite of the language barrier, I ended up being treated for malaria by the kind doctors there. My recovery was slow, but I was lucky because my symptoms only escalated to a sickness similar to the flu.

What most people won't tell you is that travel isn't always pretty. 

Sometimes it means risking spider, mosquito and bed bug bites (sometimes all at the same time). Getting sick and having to recover on the road is not fun. 

However, I wouldn't trade those miserable moments in exchange for all of the incredible ones I've had while exploring this big and beautiful world.

This is your sign to come to Yosemite this summer!

This year’s unusually massive snowpack is melting and the waterfalls and rivers are rushing with pure power. There hasn’t been nearly this much water in the park in decades. The waterfalls are so loud it almost sounds like an airplane is taking off! Remember to bring your waterproof hiking boots for the adventure of a lifetime! 🌲🥾

Top 5 waterfall views in Yosemite National Park:

💦 Yosemite Falls: North America's tallest waterfall cascades down in three sections. Hike to the base or take in the view from various lookout points.

💦 Bridalveil Fall: Witness this waterfall gracefully plunging 620 feet into Yosemite Valley. Take a short hike to feel the mist on your face!

💦Vernal Falls: Hike the Mist Trail to feel the power of the rushing water as you make your way up the granite steps, just be careful not to slip.

💦 Nevada Falls: Continue your adventure on the Mist Trail to reach the towering Nevada Falls. Hike up to to see panoramic vistas from the top, overlooking the Yosemite Valley.

💦 Ribbon Falls: This is one of the tallest single-drop waterfalls in North America. Since it flows off the west side of El Capitan, this is one of my absolute favorites in the park.

For a new and unique experience, you can now book a picnic right along the river at Yosemite View Lodge. When visiting Yosemite, I always stay @yosemiteviewlodge since it is a prime location at the gateway to the park and offers the perfect setting to unwind and soak in the nature.

I rarely take selfies but when I do, its exclusively with ancient monuments😆

There's nothing like stepping back in time and seeing history with my own eyes. My imagination runs wild picturing what these places looked like at the height of their civilizations. 

Here are some of my favorite places to witness history around the world: 

🇬🇧 Stonehenge, England: A mysterious prehistoric monument with colossal stone circles, sparking ongoing conversations about its intended purpose.

🇵🇪 Machu Picchu, Peru: An awe-inspiring Incan citadel perched high in the Andes, showcasing advanced ancient engineering surrounded by breathtaking panoramic views. Visit before sunset for less crowds!

🇰🇭 Angkor Wat, Cambodia: A majestic temple complex known for its intricate carvings, symbolizing the peak of Khmer civilization.

🇬🇷 The Parthenon, Greece: Located on the Athenian Acropolis, these temples represent the epitome of classical Greek architecture dedicated to the goddess Athena.

🇪🇬 Pyramids of Giza, Egypt: Crawl inside of these iconic ancient structures to begin to grasp the sheer engineering marvel of these creations that were used as tombs for Egyptian pharaohs and their treasures.

There's always a new adventure on the horizon. 🌤️

When I want to explore, I seek out opportunities where I can have real conversations and try things I've never done before. 

Here's a few ideas to jumpstart your next adventure:

 🗺️ Offbeat Destinations: Research lesser-known locations that aren't on the typical tourist path. These places will often give you more access to unique experiences and untouched beauty.

🙌 Local Recommendations: Connect with locals on social media or in person to ask for insider tips on hidden gems, restaurants, etc. 

🎉 Festivals: Time your travels to coincide with local festivals/celebrations. This is one of the most reliable ways to guarantee an immersive and authentic cultural experience.

👣 Gut Walks: This may sound funny at first but gut walks are when you go for a walk in a new place without any destination in mind. Following your intuition, you can stumble upon charming streets, markets, and local spots that aren't in mainstream tourist guides.

⛺️ Adventure Tours: Seek out tour operators that specialize in adventures like trekking or safaris in off-the-beaten-path locations.

😴 Stay in Unique Accommodations: Opt for unconventional lodgings such as boutique hotels, airbnbs or homestays that provide a distinct travel experience. 

📸 Photography: Photographers always know the best places to go for stunning views without the crowds. Even if you're not a photographer, reading photography blogs is a great place to get inspiration for your next trip. 
 
Remember, the essence of finding new adventures while traveling lies in seeking out the less-traveled paths, embracing the unfamiliar, and being open to spontaneous discoveries 🌍

What does it take to build an electric vehicle? 💭 
  I recently had the opportunity to travel to Cologne, Germany to learn about what it took to build the new, electric Ford Explorer. Since I’ll be taking this vehicle on my expedition around the world, it was fascinating to learn more about how it came to be 🛠️ 
 
The Ford design team showed me how a new vehicle goes from being an initial sketch, to a clay model, and eventually, to the final production version. In each phase, hundreds, even thousands of variations are made, tested and improved upon. This painstaking process takes years and before they’ve even released the vehicle to the public, they’re already building the next new vehicle, and they’ve got plans in the works for the one after that 🚘 🚙 
 
I even got a sneak peek at some of the next top secret projects 🤫 

Next stop, Ford’s environmental test center. This is where they test the vehicle’s endurance in freezing cold climates, scalding heat, intense wind and everything in between. An unintended side effect of this trip was that I definitely got sick after all my recent travels followed by long exposure to the crazy changes in temperature. Worth it! 🔥 ❄️ 💨 
 
Another highlight of my trip was my advanced driver training. Learning how to drift for the first time, maneuver and avoid obstacles at high speeds was so much more thrilling than I could have anticipated. 
 
Every step of the way, I met countless incredible people who have dedicated years of their lives to building the new electric Ford Explorer. I have so much respect for teams that can work together to think not in years, but in decades. 
 
It’s an honor to take their creation out into the world and push it to the limits. Stay tuned for the next update about our journey- it’s going to be a big one  🗺️

The road trip continues 🌍 

I am attempting to set the world record for the first person to circumnavigate the world in an electric vehicle. Now of course most of the earth is water and some countries are closed or unsafe, so I can't actually just drive around the globe in a straight line. To count as a circumnavigation, some of the rules are: 1) I have to drive at least 18,000 miles (which is about the distance if you could just drive across Earth by land); 2) drive in both hemispheres; 3) drive in antipodean areas (which means drive on opposite sides of the globe); and 4) drive on five continents.

Field Notes:  
 
There has been surprisingly great network of chargers along the main highways, especially closer to major cities. The load shedding in South Africa was the first major obstacle when it came to overnight charging, especially for domestic connections (household outlets). Load shedding outages are rotated on a schedule throughout the country as a way to relieve stress on a primary energy source when the demand for electricity is greater than the primary power source can supply. For my EV journey, this meant having to plan around the load shedding schedule, which is often in the middle of the night, since the power wouldn’t automatically re-start the vehicle’s charge after it was turned off. In spite of a few sleepless nights, the highlight of the trip was taking the #FordExplorer on a safari to see the incredible wildlife in the Greater Kruger National Park. 
 
Next stop: Zimbabwe 🇿🇼

Captain’s Log 4: Beitbridge Border to Harare, Zimbabwe
 
🚙 Distance Traveled:  633.8 kilometers / 393.8 miles 
Total Distance: 8162.8 kilometers  / 5072.1 miles
 
🔋 Chargers Used: 4 
Fastest AC Charger: 2.5 KW (Masvingo, Zimbabwe) 
Slowest AC Charger: 1.5 KW (Beitbridge, Zimbabwe) 
 
Country Traveled: Zimbabwe

Field Notes:  
 
Crossing the border into Zimbabwe was a huge moment for this expedition since there is nearly zero infrastructure for EV charging throughout the country.

While load shedding in South Africa took place on a schedule, here in Zimbabwe there was no schedule as load shedding happens sporadically. Without being able to anticipate when the next power outage would take place, that meant that most nights the EV would randomly stop charging since the power wouldn’t automatically re-start the vehicle’s charge after it was turned off. 

Since domestic charging (using household outlets) was the only option here, that meant I could only travel around 400 km (250 miles) on a single charge then I needed to stop for 24-30 hours to charge. While this brought my progress in terms of mileage down to a snail’s pace, it did give me time to explore some more off the beaten path areas of the country. 

After finally reaching Harare, this marked the completion of my journey on the African continent! My goal traveling from Cape Town to Harare in an EV was simple: to see what is possible to do in an EV. I’m happy to report that EV travel is very possible here, albeit quite slow in countries like Zimbabwe where you have to rely solely on domestic charging. 

Can you guess which continent I’m heading to next?

13 years ago, I visited Australia for the first time. I went on a road trip with my parents along the Great Ocean Road. Little did I know at the time how much of an impact that experience would have on my life. 

I remember spotting some kids in their early 20's living along the beach and I had never seen anything like it. They had these old vans with surfboards strapped to the top. Their doors were slid open, showcasing cozy blankets, kitchenettes and guitars. I sat on the beach and saw them singing and dancing around a bonfire. I had never seen people look so happy and free. In that moment, my 12-year-old self made a promise that I would get to experience that level of freedom someday. 

I returned home and decided I was going to work as hard as I possibly could for the next 6 years to be able to save up enough money to travel the world on my own terms. I graduated high school two years early so I could take on more full-time work before I turned 18. I would've never guessed that the gap year I dreamed of at 12 years old would lead me to every country in the world. 

That's also why feels very full circle to be back in Australia now, living out an entirely new dream. 

If you've ever been like me, a little kid sitting on a beach with a head full of big dreams, just know it's never too late to start chasing🌏🏃‍♀️✨

Field Notes:  
 
After relying solely on household outlets for charging in Zimbabwe, driving my EV in Australia has been a much needed respite from the slow charging speeds. 

Australia is a massive continent which meant I had a lot of ground to cover. Once in Queensland, I found myself driving the world's longest electric vehicle super highway in a single state/region! This made charging a breeze and gave me so much extra time to explore the coastline.

I met up with a representative from Record Setter to track my progress so far and I have now officially reached 45% of the way through my journey. This felt like such a significant milestone after spending countless hours on the road over the past 66 days. 

Reaching Cairns marked the ending of my drive in Australia but as a very aptly placed road sign mentioned, "still a long way to go kids!"

Exploring Varanasi’s ghats along the sacred Ganges river✨

This was the perfect place to dive into the rich spiritual and cultural tapestry of India🇮🇳

Varanasi, one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world, is known for its ghats, which are series of steps leading down to the holy river.

Each ghat has its own unique charm and significance. Dashashwamedh Ghat is famous for the Aarti ceremony, a daily ritual of prayers, yoga, meditation and chants during sunrise. 

Manikarnika Ghat holds immense religious importance as the main cremation ghat. It is believed that those who are cremated here attain moksha, liberation from the cycle of rebirth. 

For centuries, people have traveled from all across the world to experience the cremation rituals, receive blessings from holy men, take spiritual baths in the Ganges, and visit the many temples along the water.

Wandering along the Ganges was a profound experience that I won’t forget any time soon.

A city where life and death collide in ways I’m still searching for words to describe...

It's been a long time since I've been somewhere as complex, confronting and utterly confounding as Varanasi. 

While death is on full display, I found no shortage of kindness and joy in the eyes of holy men and those who have come to bathe in the sacred waters of the Ganges. 

Thousands of pilgrims travel to Varanasi, considered India's holiest city, to die. It is believed that those who are cremated here attain moksha or liberation from the cycle of rebirth.

Witnessing everything from deep mourning to colorful rituals and even port-mortem cannibalism in a single afternoon caused a whirlwind of emotions that I’m grateful to have had the opportunity to feel.

Adventure is out there!🎈🗺️ 

What is your favorite Pixar film?😍

The struggle is real😅⬇️

There is infrastructure for charging EVs in bigger cities across Northern India however there was one major problem... They haven't been compatible with my car specifically since it is a pre production vehicle. This meant that my EV wasn't able to communicate with most of the charging stations within this country specifically. Tension has been at an all time high and this made my range anxiety go through the roof, especially since the clock was ticking before our permits expired to cross the border into Bhutan.

I have support vehicles, filmmakers, medics, security, a mechanic and an EV technician traveling with me on this adventure. Along with all sorts of things needed in case of emergencies, like spare tires and parts, we have a portable battery unit. This power-bank works on the same principle as the one you use to charge your phone when your battery is running low but this one is just a lot bigger.

One of the questions I’ve been asked in previous videos is what happens if the car runs out of power and this is our only solution. The portable battery gives about 12 km of range after 1 hour of charging which is hopefully enough to get us to the nearest charger or a plug socket. Every little bit helps!

By the way, this power-bank is fully electric ⚡️
